<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: HOCKEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Pittsburgh Penguins obtained defenseman Larry Murphy and Peter Taglianetti 
in a trade with the Minnesota North Stars for defenseman Jim Johnson and Chris 
Dalhquist. Murphy, 29, was the Kings' No. 1 pick in the 1980 draft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA121290-0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 320954 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 12, 1990, Wednesday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 14; Column 5 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
240 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN FERNANDO ADDS TEAMS TO ITS BASEBALL TOURNAMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE ELLING 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
San Fernando High's preseason baseball tournament has been expanded to eight 
teams and may add more teams in the spring of 1992, according to Tiger Coach 
Steve Marden. 
</P>
<P>
The spring tournament, in its second season, will include City Section teams 
Grant, Birmingham, Granada Hills, Kennedy, Narbonne, Franklin, Poly and San 
Fernando. 
</P>
<P>
The inaugural Tiger Invitational featured a six-team field, and Marden said 
that, based on feedback, he may expand the tournament to 10 or 12 teams in 
1992. Marden said coaches like the fact that the tournament lasts just eight 
days, rather than continuing over several consecutive weekends and into the 
regular-season schedule. 
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes in those tournaments, you end up using a second baseman or an 
outfielder on the hill," Marden said. "Nobody wants to use their best pitcher 
when they might have an important league game coming up. This tournament 
doesn't drag on forever." 
</P>
<P>
Each team is guaranteed four games in the tournament, which runs Feb. 20, 21, 
26 and 28. Also, area teams have been guaranteed that they will not face a 
league opponent. San Fernando, which was 3-0-1 in tournament play last season, 
is the defending champion. 
</P>
<P>
Marden said that a handful of Southern Section teams from the area inquired 
about entering but are prohibited from playing until March 7. 
</P>
<P>
The tournament could help fill the void created when the Thousand Oaks 
tournament folded over the summer. STEVE ELLING 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
