<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
SAN DIEGO; 
</P>
<P>
CITY MANAGER TO RETIRE IN MARCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
City Manager John Lockwood, who rose from mail clerk to the city's top 
administrator, said he will retire March 9, the day before he turns 60. 
</P>
<P>
After 37 years in city government, Lockwood became city manager in October, 
1986, after the forced resignation of Sylvester Murray, a nationally recognized 
administrator who clashed with the City Council. As a top administrator, 
Lockwood earned $126,372 annually and directed 9,000 employees and a 
$1.2-billion budget. One of Lockwood's top achievements was a major "customer 
service" effort in 1988 to improve contact with the public. The program cut red 
tape in the Building Inspection Department and put uniforms on Balboa Park 
employees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
