307 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE: MULLEN NEW CHIEF OF MAY CO., CALIFORNIA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GEORGE WHITE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
May Department Stores Co. has appointed David P. Mullen to succeed Kenneth F. 
Sokol, who is retiring as president and chief executive of its Los 
Angeles-based May Co., California division. 
</P>
<P>
Mullen, previously was president of Filene's, a 19-store May Department Stores 
division based in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
He will assume his new position on Jan. 15. May Co. California includes 37 
stores in Southern California and Nevada. 
</P>
<P>
Mullen, 56, began his career with the Cleveland-based Higbee's department store 
chain, serving in a variety of merchandising positions before joining the 
Washington-based Woodward &amp; Lothrop department store chain in 1972. He was 
named president of Woodward &amp; Lothrop in 1972. He joined the St. 
Louis-based May Department Stores in 1988 as president of the Phoenix-based 
Goldwaters department store division, relinquishing the post the same year to 
take the position at Filene's. 
</P>
<P>
Sokol, 62, is retiring after a 31-year career with May Department Stores. He 
joined the California division as a buyer in 1960 and subsequently held 
merchandising positions at three May Department Store divisions. He returned to 
May Co. as president of the Southland retailing operation in February, 1986. 
</P>
<P>
The division's sales grew steadily during Sokol's tenure, said Richard L. 
Battram, vice chairman of May Department Stores. The California division had 
sales of $740 million when Sokol was named president in 1986. Sales in the 
current fiscal year are expected to reach the $1-billion level, Battram said. 
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts said Sokol is leaving the division in a relatively strong 
competitive state. 
</P>
<P>
Edgar S. Mangiafico continues as chairman of May Co., California. 
</P>
<P>
May Co. -- the third largest division within the 303-store May Department 
Stores chain -- had sales of $954 million in the fiscal year ended Feb. 3. 
GEORGE WHITE 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Kenneth F. Sokol 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Appointment 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA121290-0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 321301 </DOCID>
