<HEADLINE>
<P>
STATE; 
</P>
<P>
STUDY CITES PRE-QUAKE TREMORS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A series of medium-size tremors may presage big quakes in California, and the 
telltale pattern might be used to improve predictions of when devastating 
quakes will strike, scientists said today. 
</P>
<P>
A historical study of tremor activity surrounding the major San Francisco Bay 
quakes of 1868, 1906 and 1989 found the number of moderate earthquakes 
increased rapidly on nearby faults one to two decades before the serious 
quakes. 
</P>
<P>
After the 1868 and 1906 quakes struck, seismic activity dropped off sharply and 
there were relatively few quakes for periods of 13 years and 42 years, 
respectively, the study showed. 
</P>
<P>
A comparable pattern was also found for the sizable 1948 shock on the San 
Andreas Fault in Southern California, Lynn Sykes and Steven Jaume wrote in 
their study published in the journal Nature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
